<div type="definition">
<p>ILLNESS in the form of an OPEN WOUND CAUSED by INFLAMMATION. [MEDICINE]</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for an ulcer of any kind is chuāng 瘡.</p>
<p>2. Jū 疽 refers to a deep-rooted ulcer that is not only malignant but also very hard to cure and extremely dangerous, leading usually to the death of the patient.</p>
<p>3. Cuó 痤 refers any small but highly malignant ulcer, often leading to the death of the patient.</p>
<p>4. Dīng 疔 refers to a small and superficial but malignant ulcer. This can be treated but is highly dangerous when not treated in time.</p>
<p>5. Jiè 疥 refers to a malignant ulcer of any provenance that has spread to several places.</p>
<p>6. Bǐ 疕 refers specifically to an ulcer on the head.</p>
<p>7. Yáng 瘍 refers to a malignant ulcer sent down by ghosts or devils.</p>
        </div>
